.chap(Advanced Features and Programmer Aids,advanced)

This chapter covers some information necessary
for certain kinds of programming in PPL.
In previous sections, some explanations have purposely
been incomplete so as to avoid cluttering them
with extraneous detail.  We shall now complete these
explanations.  Several built-in functions not previously
mentioned are also covered.  The user is urged to
consult {"Appendix!" appbuiltin} for a complete list of
built-in functions.

.sec(Advanced Debugging Facilities,stoptrace)
.see debugging,|STOP, TRACE|

To supplement PPL's extensive editing
facilities and conversational mechanics, a set
of debugging features have been included;
collectively they are known as !<stop and trace>.

To activate and deactivate the
stop and trace features, there exist four
built-in functions:  ~<<STOP>~, ~<<UNSTOP>~, ~<<TRACE>~, and ~<<UNTRACE>~.
Each of these functions takes a function name
as its first argument, !<preceded by a dollar sign>,
.x dollar sign,preceding function name in STOP and TRACE
and optionally some
additional integer arguments which
designate the numbers of statements to be
affected.
If no integer arguments are furnished, all
steps of the function designated by the first
argument are affected.  For example:

.begin indent 8,30 tabs 31
3STOP($F, 1, 3, 4, 7)\1Marks steps 1, 3, 4, and 7
of the function ~F~ to stop.

3STOP($G)\1Marks all steps of the function
~G~ to stop.

3UNSTOP($G, 4, 5)\1Removes the stop codes
from statements 4 and 5 of the function ~G~.

3TRACE($G)\1Marks all steps of ~G~ for tracing.

3UNTRACE($G, 3)\1Removes the trace code from statement
3 of ~G~.
.end

If step !<n> of function ~F~ is marked for tracing,
then, after each execution of that statement,
PPL will print 3F[!<n>]1 followed by the value of the
statement on line !<n> of ~F~.  All statements
in PPL have printable values. Non-value-returning
.xx TRACE,value,of statement in
.xx IF form,NULL,value of
.xx FOR form,NULL,value of
.xx WHILE form,NULL,value of
.xx REPEAT form,NULL,value of
procedure calls, conditionals in which the
condition evaluates to ~FALSE~ and there is no
~ELSE~ expression, and ~FOR~, ~WHILE~, and ~REPEAT~ forms
all have the value ~NULL~.
In the case of
assignment statements the value of the right hand
side is printed, and in the case of ~@/<GOTO,value/of>~s the
number of the target statement is printed.

When step !<n> of the function ~F~ is marked
to stop, an attempt to execute step 3F[!<n>]1 will
cause the function to be suspended;
.x suspension,by STOP
control will be passed to the user in the environment of
suspension exactly as if he had stopped execution himself.
The suspension occurs !<before> the execution of
statement 3F[!<n>]1.
At this point, values of variables may be
examined and reset and expressions may be computed
in the environment of suspension.
Execution may be resumed by calling the built-in function
~<<RESUME>~, or may be started at another statement
by executing 3<<GOTO>#%!<k>1, where !<k> is a statement number.
All this has already been explained in
the presentation of user suspension in {"Section!" suspension}.

If ~STOP~, ~UNSTOP~, ~TRACE~, or ~UNTRACE~
is called with improper second and succeeding
arguments (e.g. statement numbers out of range,
or non-integers), an error will result and one
cannot be assured that the designated
operation has taken place properly.

After editing a function, the stop and
.x editing,effect on STOP and TRACE
.x STOP,effect of editing
.x TRACE,effect of editing
trace codes of every statement of that function
are reinitialized to the 'off' condition.
This is because statements may have been
altered, deleted, or renumbered.

In the following example, we use ~TRACE~ to trace
the flow of control through a slightly modified version of the ~EUCLID~ function
defined in {"Section!" gotos}:

.examp
\$<<EUCLID>(M,N); R
   [1]\R _ M-N*IDIV(M,N)
   [2]\IF R=0 THEN RETURN N
   [3]\M_N
   [4]\N_R
   [5]\GOTO %1
   [6]\$

.apart group
\TRACE($EUCLID)
\EUCLID(544,119)
EUCLID[1] 68
EUCLID[2] NULL
EUCLID[3] 119
.apart
EUCLID[4] 68
EUCLID[5] 1
EUCLID[1] 51
EUCLID[2] NULL
EUCLID[3] 68
EUCLID[4] 51
EUCLID[5] 1
EUCLID[1] 17
EUCLID[2] NULL
EUCLID[3] 51
.group
EUCLID[4] 17
EUCLID[5] 1
EUCLID[1] 0
EUCLID[2] 17
17
.end

Since ~STOP~ and ~TRACE~ are line-oriented,
they are clearly easiest to use when the ~STOP~ped and ~TRACE~d
statements are very simple.  In multiple expressions, for example,
only the value of the last expression will be printed out by ~TRACE~.

In the PDP-10 version, the function ~BACKTRACE~ is provided
as an additional debugging feature.
.x BACKTRACE
Calling ~BACKTRACE~ has the effect of printing the names and current
step numbers of all functions entered, starting with the most
recent.
This is particularly valuable when computation has been suspended
in order to follow the execution path to the point of the error.

.sec(Environmental Inquiries,envinq)

The following built-in parameterless procedures return ~<<TUPLE>~s of ~<<STRING>~s
enumerating all instances of particular classes of definitions
in the current environment (available in the PDP-10 version only):

.begin indent 0,20 tabs 21
~<<FUNCTIONS>~\Returns a list of all the user-defined functions known to PPL.

~<<VARIABLES>~\Returns a list of all defined !<global> @<variable,global>s, i.e.
all variables except those local to the current function (if any).

~<<DATA.DEFINITIONS>~\Returns a list of all data definitions made by the user,
including structure, sequence, and alternate definitions.
.end

There are also several functions for obtaining more information
about the class of object denoted by a particular @@<identifier,class of>.*<At
present, these functions operate correctly only for global identifiers.>
Each function returns ~TRUE~ if the object belongs to the stated class
and ~FALSE~ otherwise;  in no case will an error result.
Of the following functions, only ~UNASSIGNED~ is implemented
in the PDP-11 version.

.begin indent 0,20 tabs 21
{fn(UNASSIGNED,x)}\Returns ~TRUE~ if the identifier !<x> has not been defined
in any way (or has been ~ERASE~d).

{fn(VARIABLE,x)}\Returns ~TRUE~ if !<x> is the name of a variable.

{fn(SYSTEM.FN,x)}\Returns ~TRUE~ if !<x> is the name of a built-in function.

{fn(USER.FN,x)}\Returns ~TRUE~ if !<x> is the name of a user-defined function.

{fn(ATOMIC.TYPE,x)}\Returns ~TRUE~ if !<x> is one of the built-in atomic
data type names (~INT~, ~REAL~, ~DBL~, ~CHAR~, ~BOOL~, or ~NONE~).

{fn(COMPOSITE.TYPE,x)}\Returns ~TRUE~ if !<x> is the name
of a structure or sequence definition (including the built-in
definitions ~STRING~ and ~TUPLE~).

{fn(ALTERNATE.TYPE,x)}\Returns ~TRUE~ if !<x> is the name of an
alternate definition (including the built-in alternate definitions
~ATOMIC~, ~STRUCTURE~, ~SEQUENCE~, ~V.SEQUENCE~, and ~GENERAL~).

{fn(SELECTOR.NAME,x)}\Returns ~TRUE~ if !<x> is the name of a selector defined
in one or more structure definitions.

{fn(CLASS,x)}\Returns a ~STRING~ describing the class of the variable !<x>.
This ~STRING~ consists of the name of whichever of the above
functions would have returned ~TRUE~ if given !<x> as an argument;
i.e. the result will be one of ~"UNASSIGNED"~, ~"VARIABLE"~, etc.
.end

.sec(Copying and Sharing,copshr)
.xx data,copying,of
.xx data,sharing,of

In writing programs using many varieties of data
one discovers that sometimes one wants to copy substructures
of structures and, on other occasions, one wants to share
the use of certain substructures among several structures or
variables.  For example, in matrix manipulation (and indeed
in almost all kinds of arithmetic such as formula or polynomial
arithmetic) one wants to copy substructures.
Suppose we have issued the following statements:

.examp
\$<<VECTOR> = [1: ] INT

\$<<ARRAY> = [1: ] VECTOR

\M_ARRAY(VECTOR(32,57),VECTOR(),VECTOR(1,2,3,4))
\V_M[3]
.end

When one extracts the ~VECTOR V~ that is the
third row of the ~ARRAY M~, under most circumstances
the value ~V~ should be a !<copy> of the third row of ~M~.
If ~V~ were to !<share> the same row vector as the third row of
~M~, then any @<assignment,retroactive> of new components to ~V~ would
retroactively change components of ~M[3]~, an undesirable behavior.
On the other hand,
sharing is just the relationship that permits changes in
components to be transmitted to all owners of a shared substructure.
If for example, the title, author and subject cards in a library
card catalog could share common information about a book in the
form of a shared substructure, then a change in information about
the book could be made once instead of three times.
This arrangement saves time and space.

.ssec(Non-Copy Assignment,noncopy)

In PPL, a measure of control exists over the choice
between !<copying> and !<sharing> of structures at the time of assignment.
In particular, expressions of the form !<v>_!<e> cause the value of the
expression !<e> to be copied before being assigned to be the value of !<v>,
whereas expressions of the form !<v>__!<e> cause the value of the
expression !<e> to be assigned as the value of !<v> !<without> first copying it.
This latter form of @<assignment,non-copy> is called !<non-copy assignment>.
It is used to set up sharing relationships.

The following example makes use of the definitions
of ~VECTOR~ and ~ARRAY~ that were made in
the previous example.

.examp
.tabs 9,35
\M_ARRAY(VECTOR(11,12,13),VECTOR(21,22))
\V_M[1]\7A !<copy> of M[1] is assigned to V.3
\V[2]_99\7A component of V is replaced.3
\V
[11,99,13]
\M\7Note that M is unchanged;3
[[11,12,13],[21,22]]\7   only the copy in V was changed.3
.apart group
\V__M[1]\7Now V !<shares> the value of M[1].3
\V[2]_99
\V
[11,99,13]
\M\7M[1,2] now reflects the change made3
[[11,99,13],[21,22]]\7   to V[2], since V and M[1] share
\\   the same value.
.end

Non-copy assignment can also be used to set up @<data structures,cyclic> containing cycles and to model <<pointer>s. For
example:

.examp
\Y_[23,0,-99]
\Y[2]__Y
.end

The last statement above causes ~Y[2]~ to share
the value of ~Y~;
this is what is known as an !<infinite regress>.
.x infinite regress

Pointers can be modeled by use of sharing as follows
(note:  the use of 3$X1 as a dummy argument is
explained in Section {subsection! callbyref}).

.examp
.tabs 9,33
\$PTR = [VAL:GENERAL]

\$MKREF($X)
   [1]\MKREF_PTR(0)\7Makes PTR with 0 as value.3
   [2]\MKREF[VAL]__X\7Shares referent X as value3
   [3]\$7\   of pointer.
.end

Once we have made these definitions, 3R__MKREF(X)1 creates a pointer
to a datum X, and 3VAL(R)1 acts on the reference ~R~ to recover
the value ~X~. Thus, a ~PTR~ is an object, usable as a component of another object,
having a value, ~VAL~, which designates a second object ~X~ by sharing.

It is important to note that non-copy assignment
results in a !<sharing> relationship and not an !<equivalence>
relationship.  That is, the statement

.examp
\A__B
.end

does not mean "make ~A~ and ~B~ be the same variable";
rather it means "make ~A~ share the current value of ~B~".
Thus, if we later assign a new value to ~B~, e.g.

.examp
\B_COMPLEX(X/Y,34.7)
.end

this causes no change in the value of ~A~.
The value of ~A~ continues to be the datum that
was assigned to it;  it is no longer shared
because the sharing relationship between ~B~ and that datum
has been broken.

.ssec(Calls by Value and by Reference,callbyref)

The issue of copying versus sharing
also arises in parameter passing when
making a function call.
.xx function call,copying,in
.xx function call,sharing,in
PPL allows the user a choice of whether
or not arguments are to be copied before
being passed to a subroutine.

The normal convention is known as
!<call by value>, which means that the callee
.x call by value
.x value,call by
is provided only with a copy of the value of the argument;
no other information about the corresponding
actual parameter is passed.
As explained in {"Section!" functiondef}, the %<dummy/argument>s
are simply
initialized with copies of the values of the
calling parameters;  from then on they
behave as locals.
Thus, PPL's normal convention
with regard to parameter passing is
one of copying each argument before
making the call.

The other system is known as
!<call by reference>.
.x call by reference
.x reference,call by
A parameter passed by reference is not copied
and retains the information necessary
to access the actual parameter directly.

The user indicates, at function
definition time, which arguments
are to be passed by reference.
This is done by preceding each such
dummy argument by a @@<dollar sign,signalling argument passed by reference> in the
function header line.  All other arguments will
be passed by value as usual.

The following examples illustrate
the behavior of call by reference
as opposed to call by value.

.examp
.tabs 9,35
\$<<CBV>(A,B,C)\7Example of call by value3
   [1]\A_3.4
   [2]\B[3]_5
   [3]\C_C+1
   [4]\$

.apart group
\X_1.0
\Y_[1,2,3,4]
\Z_[3,2,4,1]
\CBV(X,Y,Z[3])
\X
1.\\7Note unchanged calling parameters3
\Y
[1,2,3,4]
\Z
[3,2,4,1]

.apart group
\$<<CBR>($A,$B,$C)\7Example of call by reference3
   [1]\A_3.4
   [2]\B[3]_5
   [3]\C_C+1
   [4]\$

.apart group
\CBR(X,Y,Z[3])
\X
3.4\\7Note effect of call by reference3
\Y
[1,2,5,4]
\Z
[3,2,5,1]
.end

Call by reference is actually somewhat more powerful
than the above examples would indicate.
Arguments passed by reference may include
such things as @@<function name,passed by reference>s and @@<selector,passed by reference>s,
which are not assignable quantities in PPL.
For example, the following function, {fn(MAPCAR,f,l)},
takes as its arguments a function !<f> and a ~TUPLE~ !<l>.
It returns a ~TUPLE~ constructed by distributively applying the function !<f>
to each element of !<l>.
.x distributive application of function to TUPLE
This operates correctly only because the function
name is passed by reference.

.examp
\$MAPCAR($F,L); I
   [1]\MAPCAR_MAKE(TUPLE,LENGTH(L),0)
   [2]\FOR I_1:LENGTH(L) DO MAPCAR[I]_F(L[I])
   [3]\$

\X_[1,2,3,4,5]
\MAPCAR(SQRT,X)
[1.,1.414214,1.732051,2.,2.236068]
.end

.ssec(RETURN,returnbyref)
.xx reference,RETURN,by

Values returned by use of the ~RETURN~ statement (as opposed to
being assigned to the procedure identifier) are always returned
by reference, in a manner analogous to making calls by reference.
By this means, one may write functions that return the names of
other functions, predicates, selector names, and so forth as their
results.

The built-in function {fn(SRETURN,e)} has precisely the same effect as the statement ~RETURN~ !<e>.  It is included so as to permit one to define a unary operator invoking the ~RETURN~ operation.

.ssec(IDENTICAL,identical)

To permit programs to detect the existence of sharing relationships, the built-in function {fn(IDENTICAL,a,b)} returns ~TRUE~ if !<a> and !<b> share the same value.*<At present, IDENTICAL is implemented only in the PDP-10 version.>  Among other things, this facilitates writing user programs to operate on cyclic or reentrant data structures.  Note that ~ATOMIC~ objects with the same value are identical by definition, since they are semantically indistinguishable.  For example:

.examp
\X_[1,2,3,4,5]
\Y_X; Z__X
\IDENTICAL(X,Y)
FALSE
\IDENTICAL(X,Z)
TRUE
.end

.sec(Functions Taking Variable Numbers of Arguments,tuparg)

In the PDP-10 version, it is possible to define functions which
may be called with an indefinite number of arguments, in
a manner similar to calling built-in %<variadic/function>s such
as ~<<ERASE>~ and ~<<PRINT>~.  For example, suppose we wish to define
a procedure called ~<<MAX>~ which takes an arbitrary number of
numeric arguments and returns their maximum.  This may be
accomplished as follows:

.examp
\$MAX(A,[B); I
   [1]\MAX_A
   [2]\FOR I_1:LENGTH(B) DO IF B[I]>MAX THEN MAX_B[I]
   [3]\$

\MAX(23,57)
57
\MAX(99,48,29,187,35+8,157-85)
187
.end

As is demonstrated above, a user-defined function is made
variadic by prefixing the !<last> %<dummy/argument> with a left
@@<square bracket,distinguishing variadic function>.  When the function is called, the corresponding
actual parameter and all remaining arguments are collected together
and passed as a ~@@<TUPLE,in variadic function call>~.  It is up to the function to enumerate the
components of this ~TUPLE~ and perform whatever processing is
appropriate.

To clarify the operation of this form of parameter passing, we
might set a stop code in the function ~MAX~ so as to be able to
examine the value of the parameter ~B~:

.examp
\<<STOP>($MAX,1)
\MAX(23,57)
STOPPED BEFORE EXECUTING MAX[1]
\B
[57]
\RESUME
57
.apart group
\MAX(99,48,29,187,35+8,157-85)
STOPPED BEFORE EXECUTING MAX[1]
\B
[48,29,187,43,72]
\RESUME
187
.apart group
\MAX(123)
STOPPED BEFORE EXECUTING MAX[1]
\B
[]
\RESUME
123
.end

.sec(EXECUTE,execute)

PDP-10 PPL contains a built-in function {fn(EXECUTE,s)} which accepts a ~@@<STRING,argument to EXECUTE>~ !<s> as its
argument and causes the text of the ~STRING~ to be executed
as PPL statements, exactly as if these statements had been typed
directly by the user.  For example:

.examp
\EXECUTE("1+2")
3
\A_CONCAT("B_111+", MAKE(STRING,10,'3))
\EXECUTE(A)
\B
3333333444
.end

If PPL encounters a &/<syntax error/in/EXECUTE> while evaluating text supplied to
~EXECUTE~, the appropriate error message will be printed and
a corrected version of the text will be requested from the user.

The ~EXECUTE~ function is useful in a wide variety of ways.
For example, one may manufacture new variable names and other
identifiers from ~STRING~s:

.examp
\EXECUTE("A") _ 2
\A
2
\S_"I AM A STRING"
\EXECUTE(TYPE(S))('X, 'Y, 'Z)
XYZ
.end

.x TYPE,used with EXECUTE
The second example deserves some explanation.  The expression
3TYPE(S)1 returns the type of the variable ~S~
as a ~STRING~;  i.e. it returns ~"STRING"~.  Then ~"STRING"~ is passed
as an argument to ~EXECUTE~ and is evaluated to the identifier ~STRING~.
Hence the effect of the entire statement is equivalent to

.examp
\STRING('X, 'Y, 'Z)
.end

.x constructor function,STRING
i.e. a call to the constructor function ~STRING~.

This sort of construction is particularly useful in writing
general-purpose functions for performing operations on any of
a wide range of data types.  For example, suppose we want
a function {fn(APPEND,s,e)} which appends the element !<e> to the
variadic sequence !<s>, regardless of the actual type of !<s>.
(Of course, !<e> must be legal as a component of !<s>.)
This may be accomplished as follows:

.examp
\$APPEND($S,E)
   [1]\S _ <<CONCAT>(S, EXECUTE(TYPE(S))(E))
   [2]\$

\Z_"ABC"
\APPEND(Z,'D)
\Z
ABCD
\T_[2, "QQQ", Z]
\APPEND(T, S)
\T
[2,QQQ,ABCD,I AM A STRING]
.end

Another use of ~EXECUTE~ is to construct and execute a PPL statement
from fragments obtained from the user via the
.x STRING demand symbol
.x demand symbol,STRING
~STRING~ demand symbol (?").
For example, the following procedure, ~<<INTUPLE>~, returns as a ~TUPLE~
a sequence of data items input by the user on a single line, separated
by commas.

.examp
\$INTUPLE
   [1]\INTUPLE _ EXECUTE(CONCAT("[", CONCAT(?", "]")))
   [2]\$

\INTUPLE
      ?\2, 4, 6+1, "HELLO", COMPLEX(3.1, 4.7)
[2,4,7,HELLO,[RP:3.1,IP:4.7]]
.end

The text evaluated by ~EXECUTE~ may include function and data definitions.
.x function definition,and EXECUTE
.x data definition,and EXECUTE
Hence it is possible to create new functions at execution time:

.examp
.tabs 9,30
\PROG _ "$F(X) %
\F_2*X %
\$ %
\"
\PROG
$F(X)
F_2*X
$
\TYPE(PROG)
STRING
\EXECUTE(PROG)
\?F

\$F(X)
   [1]\F_2*X
\$
.end

For convenience in calling built-in functions that require identifiers
(e.g. function names) as arguments, such as ~<<UNARY>~, ~<<BINARY>~, ~<<MAKE>~, etc.,
the PDP-10 version allows the user to supply ~STRING~s in those argument positions.
Such ~STRING~s are automatically evaluated to identifiers
.x STRING,automatic evaluation to identifier
.x identifier,use of STRING in place of
as if ~EXECUTE~ had been applied to them.  Hence,

.examp
\BINARY("+", "ADD")
\MAKE("VECTOR", 10, 123.4)
.end

is precisely the same*<With the exception that the former example
takes longer to execute because of the identifier lookups that
PPL must perform.> as:

.examp
\BINARY("+", ADD)
\MAKE(VECTOR, 10, 123.4)
.end

This feature is handy for making use of the results of built-in
functions that return the names of identifiers as ~STRING~s, such as
~<<TYPE>~, ~<<UNARY.DEF>~, ~<<BINARY.DEF>~, etc.  For example, here is a function
{fn(COPY.BINARY.OP,a,b)}, which defines the operator !<b> (expressed as a ~STRING~)
to be the same as the existing binary operator !<a>:

.examp
\$COPY.BINARY.OP(A,B)
   [1]\BINARY(B,BINARY.DEF(A),BINARY.PREC(A),ASSOCIATIVITY(A))
   [2]\$

\2^13
8192
\COPY.BINARY.OP("^", "**")
\2**13
8192
.end

For other examples of the use of this feature, the user should
display the definitions of the built-in functions
~<<RENUMBER>~ and ~<<IVERSONIAN>~ (described in {"Section!" iversonian}).

.sec(Unevaluated Identifiers,uneval)

In previous sections we have presented several built-in
functions that take the names of other functions
as arguments; for example, ~ERASE~ ({"Section!" erasing})
and the stop/trace functions ({"Section!" stoptrace}).
In these explanations the user was
warned always to precede the names of functions with
a dollar sign when using them as arguments to other
functions.

An identifier preceded by a @@<dollar sign,denoting unevaluated identifier> is called
an !<unevaluated identifier>; i.e. the dollar
.x unevaluated identifier
.x identifier,unevaluated
sign prevents the immediate evaluation of the identifier
upon its being encountered.

If ~F~ is a user-defined function, the statement

.examp
\@@<ERASE,and unevaluated identifiers>(F)
.end

causes the current definition of ~F~ to be erased.
If ~F~ is a function of one or more arguments, it
is easy to distinguish a !<call> of ~F~
.x function call,distinguished from function name
.x function name,distinguished from function call
(with arguments) from the use of '~F~' to designate its own
name, since all calls of ~F~ must be accompanied by argument lists.
However, if ~F~ is a %<parameterless/procedure> (i.e. it takes
no arguments), the call of ~F~ and the use of ~F~ to denote its
own name coincide.  In this case, by convention,
the use of ~F~ denotes the !<call> of the parameterless
procedure ~F~, rather than the !<name> '~F~'.
In order to use ~F~ as a name (e.g. passed as an argument
to another function), it is necessary to precede the
name by a dollar sign to inhibit its immediate evaluation.

For example, if ~F~ is a parameterless procedure
and we issue the statement

.examp
\ERASE(F)
.end

PPL will first evaluate
~F~ (by calling the function ~F~ so as to return
a value), then will try to ~ERASE~ the value
returned by ~F~; this will cause an execution error.
On the other hand, if we type

.examp
\ERASE($F)
.end

the dollar sign will indicate to PPL that
the function ~F~ is not to be called but rather
that the !<name> ~F~ is to be passed directly
as a parameter to ~ERASE~.

If the function ~F~ takes arguments,
then this difficulty does not arise; i.e.
the statement

.examp
\ERASE(F)
.end

is unambiguously interpreted to mean "erase the name ~F~";
the use of ~F~ could not possibly denote a function call
because there is no argument list following the name.
However, it is recommended that the user always precede
function names used as arguments by dollar signs
even in this case.
Doing so will develop a regular habit
and reduce the possibility of forgetting
the dollar sign in the cases in which it
is actually needed.

.sec(Further Information on ERASE,moreerase)

While we are mentioning the ~<<ERASE>~ function,
we should
note that it is legal to ~ERASE~ the
meaning of almost any identifier in PPL,
including the ones corresponding to
built-in functions (e.g. ~ADD~) and values (e.g. ~TRUE~).
The only identifiers that may not be ~ERASE~d
.x ERASE,illegal arguments
are the predicates for atoms (~INT~, ~REAL~, etc.),
the built-in data definitions ~STRING~ and ~TUPLE~,
and the names used as special symbols (e.g. ~THEN~).

When ~ERASE~ing a data definition, the user
.x data definition,and ERASE
.x ERASE,and data definition
should exercise extreme caution that there exist no instances
of data constructed according to that definition.*<Failure to observe this precaution may
lead to internal errors within PPL-10 (often
a long time later).>  Generally, the only justification
for erasing a data definition is to allow a corrected
version of the same definition to be typed in,
or to entirely remove one not being used.
For further information, refer to the discussion
of system errors in {"Appendix!" appproblems}.

Occasionally it is desired to give a built-in function a new name
.x function,renaming
.x renaming function
so as to be able to use the old name of the function for
some other purpose.  The built-in function {fn(COPYSF,a,b)}, where !<b> is
the name of a built-in function, defines !<a> to be that same
function.  For example, if we wanted to change the ~<<SIN>~ function so
as to take its argument in degrees rather than radians, we might
do so as follows:

.examp
\COPYSF(<<SINRAD>,$SIN)
\ERASE($SIN)
\$SIN(N)
   [1]\SIN_SINRAD(N*PI/180)
   [2]\$
.apart skip 1 group
\PI_3.141592653589793
\SIN(90)
1.
.end

.sec(The Meaning of NULL,meaningofnull)

~@@<NULL,meaning of>~ is a somewhat artificial object
included in PPL solely to formalize
the notion of "no value".
For example, when a function that returns
no value is called, the resulting
value is ~NULL~.  Thus, if ~F~ is such
a function, the statement

.examp
\X_F(3)
.end

will cause the value ~NULL~ to be assigned
to ~X~.  Generally, this value is never printed
out unless specifically requested 
in a direct printout or via ~TRACE~ (see {"Section!" stoptrace}).
.xx NULL,printout,of

For symmetry, ~NULL~ has its own data type,
which is called ~@/<NONE,data type/>~, and is an atom;
thus, 3NULL==ATOMIC1 is ~TRUE~, and the data
definition

.examp
\$<<ATROW> = [1: ] <<ATOMIC>
.end

will allow instances of an ~ATROW~ to include
elements which are ~NULL~.

The value ~NULL~ will appear in the following cases:

.begin indent 4,8 tabs 9,25
a.\As the value of a non-value-returning
.x function,null-value-returning
procedure, i.e. a function during whose execution
the procedure identifier is never assigned a value.

b.\As the value of the @/<demand symbol,value/of blank line to> (?)
if the user's response is a blank line (i.e.
merely pressing the <<Return key>).
Note that this is not true for such a
response to the ~STRING~ demand symbol (?");
in the latter case, a ~STRING~ of length
zero will be returned, as might be expected.

c.\As the value of a conditional of the form
.xx IF form,value,of
.begin nofill select 3
\\IF !<b> THEN !<e>
.end continue
in which the expression !<b> evaluates to ~FALSE~.

d.\As the value of any ~FOR~, ~WHILE~, or ~REPEAT~ form.
.xx FOR form,value,of
.xx WHILE form,value,of
.xx REPEAT form,value,of
.end

One may test for equality with ~NULL~ just as
with other atomic values.  However, ~NULL~ is
not a legal operand to most built-in functions
and operators.

.sec(Built-In Functions for File I/O,fileio)
.x file,input and output under program control

Besides the functions for storing and retrieving entire
programs and environments, described in {"Section!" saving},
PPL also contains facilities for performing
input and output on a character or line basis under program
control.  The relevant built-in functions are as follows:

.begin indent 0,16 tabs 17
{fn(INPUT,c,s,m)}\Open the file described by the ~STRING~ !<s>
on channel !<c> for input in mode !<m>.  !<c> is a small ~INT~eger from
one to some arbitrary maximum (currently 13 in @@<PPL-10,file channel number limit> and 7 in @@<PPL-11,file channel number limit>)
representing a <<channel number>.  This number is used to refer to that open file in
all subsequent operations.  !<s> is a ~STRING~ describing the file
.x filename
in the usual way (see {"Section!" saving});  the default file extension
is ~.PPL~.
!<m>, if given, may be any atomic data type except ~NULL~
.xx file,data type,of
(i.e. ~INT~, ~REAL~, ~DBL~, ~BOOL~, or ~CHAR~), and specifies
the data type of objects to be read from
that file.  If the third argument is omitted in the call to ~INPUT~,
~CHAR~ mode is assumed by default.  For special applications
that require
%%<non-standard/byte size>s, the third argument may also be an ~INT~eger
in the range 1 to 36 specifying the byte size in bits.  In this
case, the data type for that open file will always be ~INT~.
(Non-standard byte sizes are implemented only in @@<PPL-10,non-standard byte size>
at present).

{fn(OUTPUT,c,s,m)}\Open the file described by !<s> on channel
!<c> for output in mode !<m>.  The arguments are processed as for ~INPUT~.

{fn(INBYTE,c)}\Read and return one byte through channel !<c>,
which must previously have been open for input
via a call to the ~INPUT~ function.  The data type of the
object returned is as specified in the call to ~INPUT~.

.x OUTBYTE
3OUTBYTE(2c3,2b713,2b723,...,2b7n3)1 Write the data !<b>{sub(1)}, !<b>{sub(2)}, ...#!<b>{sub(n)}
into the file open for output on channel !<c>.
Each of the arguments must be of the type specified
in the previous call to ~OUTPUT~ or an error will occur.

{fn(INSTMT,c)}\Read a line of input through channel !<c>, which
.x statement,reading from file
must be open in ~CHAR~ mode, and translate and execute it in
the environment of the call to ~INSTMT~ in exactly
the same manner as the
demand symbol (?).  If a
@@<syntax error,in INSTMT> is detected in the line so read, the normal
error message will be printed and a substitute line will
then be requested from the user's console.

{fn(INSTRING,c)}\Read a line of input through channel !<c>, which
must be open in ~CHAR~ mode, and return it as a ~@@<STRING,reading from file>~
in the manner of the
~STRING~ demand symbol (?").

.x PRINTF
3PRINTF(2c3,2d713,2d723,...,2d7n3)1 Write 7ASCII* character representations
of the data objects !<d>{sub(1)}, !<d>{sub(2)}, ...#!<d>{sub(n)} into the file on channel !<c>, which
must be open for output in ~CHAR~ mode.  ~PRINTF~ is
identical to
~<<PRINT>~ in all other respects.  Note that
function names (preceded by dollar signs) and
data definitions are legal arguments to both ~PRINT~ and
~PRINTF~, and will cause
the appropriate definitions to be printed out or written.

.x FORMATF
3FORMATF(2c3,2s713,2s723,...,2s7n3)1 Perform formatted numeric
output to the file on channel !<c>, which must be open in ~CHAR~ mode,
in a manner identical to the ~<<FORMAT>~ function.

{fn(EOF,c)}\Return ~TRUE~ or ~FALSE~ depending on
whether or not the input file on channel !<c> is at end-of-file.
Attempting to read past <<end-of-file> using
~INBYTE~, ~INSTMT~, or ~INSTRING~ will result in an error.
However, if {fn(EOF,c)} returns the value ~FALSE~, then
the next call to ~INBYTE~, ~INSTMT~, or ~INSTRING~ will always
succeed.

.x CLOSE
3CLOSE(2c713,2c723,...,2c7n3)1 Close the files on channels !<c>{sub(1)}, !<c>{sub(2)}, ...#!<c>{sub(n)},
and dissociate the channel numbers from the files, thus
freeing up the channel numbers for further use.  If ~CLOSE~
is called with no arguments (i.e. just an empty set of parentheses),
all open files (both input and output) are closed.  No error
occurs if channels specified to be ~CLOSE~d are not in fact open.

{fn(OPENED,c)}\Return ~TRUE~ or ~FALSE~ depending on whether
or not a file is open (for either input or output) on channel !<c>.

~<<FREE.CHANNEL>~\Return the number of the first free
(unused) channel, or ~NULL~ if all available channels are
in use.

{fn(POSITION,c,p)}\Position the file on channel !<c>
.see random access,POSITION
so that the !<p>th byte of the file will be the first one
read or written by the next I/O transfer operation.
If !<c> refers to an input file and !<p> is greater than the size of the file in bytes,
the {fn(EOF,c)} function will be set to return ~TRUE~ if it
is called.
~POSITION~ is implemented only for files on disk, and only for input
files in the @@<DECsystem-10,restriction on POSITION> and @@<Unix,restriction on POSITION> versions of PPL.
.end

PPL mostly follows the file I/O conventions of the operating
system under which it is running.  The following statements
are generally true in all versions of PPL.
A file may
not be open for both input and output on the same channel at the
same time.  Opening a file for output with the same name
as an existing file causes a new file to be opened, and does not
modify the existing file even after any number of ~OUTBYTE~s
or other output commands.  Only when the new output file is
~CLOSE~d does it
supercede the old version of the file.  It is therefore
possible to read the contents of the old copy of the file
at the same time as the new one is being written on
a different channel (or even after the new copy is ~CLOSE~d,
so long as the old one is opened for input before the new
one is ~CLOSE~d).  It is possible for any number of users to
have a single file open for input on any number of channels
at the same time.  However, a file may be open for output
on only a single channel at a given time.

When performing output, it is particularly important that
the file be ~CLOSE~d before PPL is exited (via calls
to ~<<SYS>~ or ~<<LOGOUT>~) or restarted (via 3<<ERASE>()1).
Otherwise, the file may not be completely written.*<In fact,
in the DECsystem-10 version of PPL, the new copy will
disappear without a trace.>

The foregoing comments apply only to files on disk.  Other
devices are somewhat more restricted.  Further information
should be obtained from the appropriate monitor reference
manuals.

In addition to the channels (1 through 7 or 13) available
by calling the ~INPUT~ or ~OUTPUT~ functions, channel @@<zero,file channel number>
refers to the controlling terminal and is always open for
both input and output in ~CHAR~ mode.  The functions ~INBYTE~,
~OUTBYTE~, ~INSTRING~, ~INSTMT~, ~PRINTF~, and ~FORMATF~ will operate
in the normal way on channel 0.  ~EOF(0)~ will always return
~FALSE~, ~OPENED(0)~ will always return ~TRUE~,
and other functions do not allow a zero channel number.

.sec(User-Defined Prompting Strings,prompting)
.xx prompt string,assignment,of

The prompts typed out by PPL to signal readiness for user
input at the top level, at user suspension level, and at demand
input level are subject to redefinition by the user.  PPL
uses the values of the identifiers ~<<TOP.PROMPT>~, ~<<SUSPEND.PROMPT>~,
and ~<<DEMAND.PROMPT>~ respectively in printing out prompts.
The user may change, say, the demand-level prompt by assigning a new
value (of type ~STRING~) to the identifier ~DEMAND.PROMPT~.
The values of these variables in the initial state of the
system (determining PPL's "normal" behavior) are as follows:

.examp tabs 9,35
\TOP.PROMPT_"        "\7[a single TAB]3
\SUSPEND.PROMPT_"     S> "
\DEMAND.PROMPT_"      ? "
.end

To completely suppress a prompt, simply assign it a null ~STRING~, i.e.

.examp
\DEMAND.PROMPT_""
.end

.sec(Special Functions,specialfns)

This section describes special built-in functions that are available
in only some versions of PPL or are otherwise restricted.
.x PPL-10,special functions
.x PPL-11,special functions

The following functions have been included to facilitate
<<partial-word processing> on PDP-10 word data.
.x byte manipulation
They are not implemented in PPL-11.

.begin indent 0,16 tabs 17
{fn(GETBYTE,f,l,i)}\From the integer !<i>, extract the !<f>th
through the !<l>th bits, and return the resulting byte as an ~INT~.
The bits are numbered 0 through 35 from left
to right.

{fn(PUTBYTE,b,f,l,i)}\Place the rightmost (!<l>-!<f>+1) bits of the
~INT~eger !<b> into bit positions !<f> through !<l> of the ~INT~eger
!<i>, and return the result as an ~INT~.
.end

The following functions perform single-character input/output
to the terminal, with no editing, buffering, or other processing
performed by the system.

.begin indent 0,16 tabs 17
~<<GETCHAR>~\Return as a ~CHAR~ the next character typed on the
.x character-at-a-time transmission
terminal by the user.

{fn(SENDCHAR,c)}\Print the ~CHAR~acter !<c> on the terminal (!<c> may also
be an ~INT~ and will be converted automatically by application
of the {fn(CHAR,c)} function).
.end


While ~GETCHAR~ and ~SENDCHAR~ are not directly implemented in
PPL-11, the ~SENDCHAR~ function can be obtained through the
use of the following built-in function.

.begin indent 0,16 tabs 17
{fn(IMAGE.OUT,c)}\Print characters on the terminal in Unix
"raw mode" which allows any 7ASCII* code to be transmitted.
In addition to the ~CHAR~ and ~INT~ arguments described for
~SENDCHAR~ above, ~IMAGE.OUT~ may also take a ~STRING~ argument,
in which case all characters in the ~STRING~ are printed in
this fashion.
.end

The following built-in functions are included in versions of
PPL-10 running on systems with 7ARDS* storage-display terminals,
.x ARDS terminal
.x graphical function
or any version in which the 7ARDS* conditional has been enabled.

.begin indent 0,16 tabs 17
~<<ARDMODE>~\Enter graphical input/output mode.

~<<TTYMODE>~\Leave graphical input/output mode.

{fn(SETPOINT,x,y)}\Set the beam to the given coordinates,
where (0,0) is in the center and useful ranges are in the order of
plus/minus 600.  ~SETPOINT~ does not intensify the beam.  To display
a dot at the selected location, ~PRINT~ a
period after performing the ~SETPOINT~ operation.

{fn(SOLIDVEC,dx,dy)}\Draw a solid vector through the given
displacement, starting at the current beam position.
Neither !<dx> nor !<dy> should exceed 1023 in magnitude.

{fn(DOTTEDVEC,dx,dy)} Draw a dotted vector through the given
displacement, starting at the current beam position.
.end

The following example draws a 50-by-50 grid on the 7ARDS*
screen:

.examp
\$<<GRID>; I
   [1]\ARDMODE
   [2]\FOR I_-500:20:500 DO SETPOINT(I,-500); SOLIDVEC(0,1000)
   [3]\FOR I_-500:20:500 DO SETPOINT(-500,I); SOLIDVEC(1000,0)
   [4]\TTYMODE
   [5]\$
.end

The following function is available on the Harvard PDP-10
only (under the 7SYLVN1 conditional).  It is for accessing
the custom-built <<Sylvania tablet> and stylus connected to
the 7ARDS* terminal.

.begin indent 0,16 tabs 17
~<<READSTYLUS>~\Interrogate the Sylvania tablet and store the
!<x>, !<y>, and !<z> coordinates of the pen in variables called
~<<XSTYLUS>~, ~<<YSTYLUS>~, and ~<<ZSTYLUS>~ respectively.
The !<x> and !<y> coordinates are similar to those for 7ARDS*
output;  the !<z> coordinate indicates height of the pen above
the tablet, where 5 to 7 indicates pen off the surface, 4 indicates
pen touching the surface, and 0 indicates pen pressed down.
.end

The following function tracks the pen with an "X" until it
.x pen tracking
is pressed down:

.examp
\$<<TRACK>
   [1]\ARDMODE
   [2]\READSTYLUS; SETPOINT(XSTYLUS,YSTYLUS)
   [3]\IF ZSTYLUS>0 THEN PRINT("X"); GOTO %2
   [4]\TTYMODE
   [5]\$
.end

The two 7ARDS* screens and the write-through (non-storage)
mode are selected via special control characters on the
7ARDS* terminal connected to the Harvard PDP-10.
The required character sequence is:

.examp
\PRINT(CHAR($35),'&,CHAR(!<n>),CHAR($34))
.end

where !<n> is taken as a 7-bit binary number whose bits have
the following significance:

.begin nofill tabs 9,21

\$100\Required bit (i.e. must be set)
\$40\Enables write-through mode
\$2\Disables scope 2
\$1\Disables scope 1
.end

The currently-selected screen(s) are erased by ~PRINT~ing
a form feed (~CHAR($14)~).

The following functions are included only in the Harvard
version of PPL-10 (under the 7FTBAKG* conditional):

.begin indent 0,16 tabs 17
~<<BACKGROUND>~\Cause PPL to enter a background running mode
whereby it runs only when no other PDP-10 time-sharing user's
program wants to run.  This is useful for long-running
compute-bound programs that seriously degrade other users' response
on very small systems such as the Harvard PDP-10.  Background
mode does not take effect until at least ten seconds of CPU
time have elapsed since the most recent command or other response
typed in by the user.

~<<FOREGROUND>~\Cancel background mode.  PPL will compete
for CPU time in the normal way.
.end

.sec(Further Information on PPL's Syntax,syntax)
.x syntax

In {"Chapter!" starting} we used such terms as !<expression>,
!<form>, and !<statement> in a rather loose
fashion.  These terms in fact have precise
meanings which we shall explain now.
A BNF formalization of PPL's syntax
is given in {"Appendix!" appsyntax}.
The explanation in this section is
a simplified, English language presentation
of the information to be found in the appendix.

In the syntax of PPL, a !<term> is the
.x term,in syntax
most basic component of a statement.
A term may be any of the following:

.begin indent 4,8 tabs 9
a.\An <<identifier> or <<constant>.

b.\A term followed by a (possibly empty)
argument list enclosed in @@<parentheses,enclosing argument list>; this
denotes a function call.

c.\A term followed by a subscript list
enclosed in @@<square brackets,enclosing selector>; this denotes a <<selection> operation.

d.\A (possibly empty) list of forms enclosed in
@@<square brackets,enclosing TUPLE>; this denotes the construction of a ~<<TUPLE>~.

e.\Any form enclosed in @@<parentheses,enclosing form>.
.end

An !<expression> is a collection of one or more
.x expression,in syntax
terms connected by zero or more unary and binary operators.
More precisely, an expression is

.begin indent 4,8 tabs 9
a.\A unary operator followed by an expression.

b.\An expression, followed by a binary operator, followed
by another expression.

c.\A term not adjacent to an operator.
.end

Thus, an expression is similar to what we consider
to be an 'algebraic expression' in mathematics.
The order of evaluation of expressions is determined by
the relative <<precedence> of the unary and binary operators involved.
It is interesting to note that the syntax of
PPL before version 40 consisted only of
terms and expressions as explained above.

A !<form> may be any of the following constructions:
.x form,in syntax

.begin indent 4,8 tabs 9
a.\The word ~<<GOTO>~ followed by an expression.

b.\The word ~<<RETURN>~, optionally followed by an expression.

c.\An expression, followed by a @@<semicolon,separating multiple expressions>, followed by
a form.

d.\The word ~IF~, followed by an expression,
.x IF form
followed by the word ~<<THEN>~, followed by a form,
optionally followed by ~<<ELSE>~ and another form.

e.\The word ~FOR~, followed by two or three expressions
.x FOR form
separated by @@<colon,separating FOR control elements>s, followed by the word ~<<DO>~, followed
by a form.
The first expression after the ~FOR~ must contain
'_' as its principal operator.
.xx FOR form,assignment operator,in

f.\The word ~WHILE~, followed by an expression, followed by the
.x WHILE form
word ~DO~, followed by a form.

g.\The word ~REPEAT~, followed by a form, followed by the word ~<<UNTIL>~,
.x REPEAT form
followed by an expression.

h.\Any expression not in one of the above contexts.
.end

Thus, forms include conditionals, ~FOR~, ~REPEAT~, and ~WHILE~ forms,
and the constructions we have been referring to as
'%<multiple/expression>s' (separated by semicolons).

Finally, a !<statement> is the highest-level
.x statement,in syntax
object in PPL's syntax;  the statement is
the smallest unit of interaction with the user
(i.e. PPL will perform computation for the user
only when he has input a complete statement).
A statement is one of the following:

.begin indent 4,8 tabs 9
a.\A form followed by a Return.
.x Return key
This is the most common statement in PPL.

b.\The word ~FOR~, followed by two or three
expressions separated by colons, followed by the word
~<<DOTHRU>~, followed by an expression designating
the line at the end of the scope, followed by a Return.
This is the
!<FOR statement> introduced in {"Section!" forstmt}.
.x FOR statement

c.\A Return.  Thus, a @/<blank line,value/of>
is a legal PPL statement
which has the value ~<<NULL>~.
.end

Any statement appearing as a step within a user-defined
function may optionally be preceded by one or more <<label>s,
where a label is an identifier immediately followed
by a @@<colon,delimiting label> (see Secion 3.5).

The user will note that the foregoing definition
of the syntax of PPL permits constructions
such as

.examp
\A_3+(IF Y=0 THEN 4.1*SIN(X) ELSE P(Y))/17.5
.end

since (1) the ~IF~ construction is a form, (2)
any form contained within parentheses is a term,
and (3) a term may be combined into an expression
with operators, etc.  This example is quite legal
and has a well-defined meaning.

In most cases, the value of a form is the value of the last expression
.xx form,value,of
executed within that form.  Thus, an ~IF~ form has
as its value the ~THEN~ clause or the ~ELSE~ clause,
depending on the value of the ~BOOL~ean
expression after the ~IF~.  (As explained in {"Section!" meaningofnull},
the value is ~NULL~ if the condition evaluates to ~FALSE~
and there is no ~ELSE~ part).
Similarly, the value of any multiple form (composed with semicolons)
is the value of the last form executed within it.
However, the value of iteration forms (~FOR~, ~WHILE~, and ~REPEAT~) is
always ~NULL~.

This generality of the syntax allows statements
of considerable power to be compressed into
very little actual text.  For example, the following
is another version of the familiar factorial function:

.examp
\$<<FACT>(N)
   [1]\FACT_(IF N<1 THEN 1. ELSE N*FACT(N-1))
   [2]\$
.end

There is no way for this manual to enumerate
all the possible variations of the syntax;
thus, the interested user is urged to experiment.
We might note that nested forms enclosed in
parentheses may be used almost everywhere;
this is particularly useful in the case of nested ~IF~
forms.  For example,
the following statements will work exactly as intended:
.xx IF form,nesting,of

.examp
\(IF Y=0 THEN P ELSE Q) _ C[IF N=1 THEN RP ELSE IP]
\R_(IF B THEN F ELSE G)(X)
.end

In the interest of conciseness, PPL
provides a number of alternative notations
for commonly used forms.  The following table
lists the correspondences:

.examp
.tabs 9,41
.x IF form,alternative notation
.x FOR form,alternative notation
.x GOTO,alternative notation
\IF !<b> THEN !<e>\!<b> => !<e>
\IF !<b> THEN !<e>{sub(1)} ELSE !<e>{sub(2)}\b => !<e>{sub(1)} :: !<e>{sub(2)}
\IF !<b> THEN GOTO %!<n>\!<b> --> %!<n>
\GOTO %!<n>\--> %!<n>
\FOR !<v> _ !<i>:!<s>:!<f> DO !<e>\!<v> _ !<i>:!<s>:!<f> ; !<e>
\FOR !<v> _ !<i>:!<s>:!<f> DOTHRU %!<n>\!<v> _ !<i>:!<s>:!<f> ;; %!<n>
.end

The '-->' operator is associated with two built-in
.x goto operator
.x operator,goto
functions:  {fn(UGOTO,n)} (for "&<unconditional/goto operator> goto")
and {fn(CGOTO,b,n)} (for "&<conditional/goto operator> goto").
'-->' is in all respects an ordinary unary and binary operator,
defined with very low precedence (see the table in {"Section!" precedence}).
.xx goto operator,precedence,of
It is provided primarily for compatibility with older versions of PPL.

As an example of a rather extreme overuse
of PPL's concise syntax features,
we present the following definition of ~<<DERIV>(F,X)~.
This function behaves identically to the one defined
in {"Section!" formula};  observe, however, that
we have succeeded in making the function
almost totally unreadable.  Further, it is more difficult
to debug (using the stop/trace feature) and to edit,
since these facilities are essentially line-oriented.
Thus, PPL leaves it up to the user to decide
the tradeoffs between conciseness, convenience, and
readability.

.examp
.tabs 9,12,15,18,21,24
\$DERIV(F,X)
   [1]\DERIV_ ( %
\\F==ATOM => (F=X => 1 :: 0) :: %
\\F==UF => UF(F[OP],F[RO]\X) :: %
\\F==BF => ( %
\\\F[OP]='+ => F[LO]\X + F[RO]\X :: %
\\\F[OP]='- => F[LO]\X - F[RO]\X :: %
\\\F[OP]='* => F[LO]*F[RO]\X + F[RO]*F[LO]\X :: %
\\\F[OP]='/ => (F[RO]*F[LO]\X - F[LO]*F[RO]\X)/ %
\\\\(F[RO]*F[RO]) ) :: %
\\"IMPROPER ARG TO DERIV")
   [2]\$
.end
